The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   BRIEFS
                  
	Tamluk, June 2: Eighteen contract labourers in a Haldia Petro unit went on a wildcat strike today after the agency that contracted them allegedly failed to clear their dues.     
	The workers at the poly poplin unit began the strike at 2pm. Subrata Panda, the owner of Eco Service, the agency that had appointed them, met Citu leaders but in vain. Management sources, however, said the impact of the strike was not felt on the companys production.         
	Krishnagar/ Bolpur: Lightning killed nine persons in Birbhum and Nadia on Monday night. Six, including a mother and son, were killed in Nadia. Three deaths were reported from Birbhum. All nine were on the field.        
	Midnapore: Sambhu Kar, a labourer, hacked his wife Anjana, 31, to death, suspecting that she was having an affair. He also injured his teenage son Biman in Debra, West Midnapore, 120km from Calcutta. Kar has apparently confessed to killing his wife.        
	Chinsurah: A gang allegedly drugged relatives of some patients at Chinsurah hospital and fled with Rs 6,500 and cellphones. Police said a group of three offered tea to the relatives, who drank it and fell unconscious on Sunday night.                                                                                                                                                                   
